Performance doesn't feel like a reason because it involves an extra check, which at best is optimized away by the JIT compiler but otherwise requires more work. What I'm referring to is snippets like:
protected Object unwrap(E object) throws ClassCastException
{
  ArgumentUtil.notNull(object, "object");
  if (object.getClass() == _elementClass)
  {
    return object.data();
  }
  else
  {
    throw new ClassCastException("Input " + object + " should be a " + _elementClass.getName());
  }
}

The point about equals is a good one. I need to think about it some more and will raise a separate conversation if enlightenment happens.
